rst2=Lucy|title=George Lucas's Blockbusting: A Decade-by-Decade Survey of Timeless Movies Including Untold Secrets of Their Financial and Cultural Success|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=London|year=2010|isbn=978-0-06-177889-6|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/georgelucassbloc00alex}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Chapman|first=James|authorlink= James Chapman (media historian) |title= Licence To Thrill: A Cultural History of the James Bond Films|publisher= [[I.B. Tauris]]|location= London |year=2009|isbn=978-1-84511-515-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Cork|first1=John|last2=Scivally|first2=Bruce|authorlink1=John Cork|title=James Bond: The Legacy|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Boxtree]]|location=London|year=2002|isbn=978-0-7522-6498-1|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/jamesbondlegacy0000cork}}\n* {{Cite book|title = The American Film Institute Catalog of Motion Pictures Produced in the United States, Part 2|last = Munden|first = Kenneth White|publisher = University of California Press|year = 1997|isbn = 978-0-5202-0970-1|location = Berkeley and Los Angeles, California|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=s1k1RsGvFwwC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|orig-year = 1976|ref=harv}}\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:James Bond in film]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by source]]\n", "name_user": "Percytown", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_James_Bond_films"}
{"title_page": "Spriggan", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox mythical creature\n|name  = Spriggan\n|image     = Spriggan sculpture by Marilyn Collins, Parkland Walk, Haringey.jpg\n|caption  = Sculpture by [[Marilyn Collins]]\n|Grouping       = [[Mythological creature]] <br/> [[Fairy]] <br/> [[Sprite (creature)|Sprite]]\n|Possibilities   = \n|AKA            = \n|Country        = [[England]]\n|Region         = [[Cornwall]]\n|Habitat        = \n|First_Reported = In folklore\n|Last_Sighted   = \n|Status         = Unconfirmed\n}}\nA '''spriggan''' {{IPAc-en|s|p|r|\u026a|d\u0292|\u0259|n}} is a [[legendary creature]] from [[Cornwall|Cornish]] [[Fairy|faery]] lore. Spriggans are particularly associated with [[West Penwith]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>Various folklore collections e.g. Craig Weatherhill and Paul Devereux, ''Myths and Legends of Cornwall'', 1994, p.23, Sigma Leisure, {{ISBN|978-1850583172}}</ref>\n\n''Spriggan'' is a dialect word, pronounced with the grapheme <gg> as /\u02a4/, sprid-jan, and not sprigg-an, borrowed from the Cornish plural ''spyrysyon'' 'spirits'.<ref>Dr Ken George, ''An Gerlyver Meur'', p. 600, Cornish Language Board, {{ISBN|978-1902917849}}</ref> \n\n==In folklore==\n\"The Spriggans are found only about the cairns, coits, or cromlechs, burrows, or detached stones, with which it is unlucky for mortals to meddle. A correspondent writes: \"This is known, that they were a remarkably mischievous and thievish tribe. If ever a house was robbed, a child kidnapped, cattle carried away, or a building demolished, it was the work of the Spriggans. Whatever commotion took place in earth, air, or water, it was all put down as the work of these spirits. Wherever the giants have been, there the Spriggans have been also. It is usually considered that they are the ghosts of the giants; certainly, from many of their feats, we must suppose them to possess a giant's strength. The Spriggans have the charge of buried treasure.<ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition, 1916, p. 81, {{ISBN|978-1605064604}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[The English Dialect Dictionary]] (1905), spriggans were apparently related to the [[troll]]s of Scandinavia.<ref name=EDD>{{cite book|editor=Wright, Joseph|title=The English Dialect Dictionary|url=https://archive.org/stream/englishdialectdi05wrig#page/690/mode/1up|volume=V|year=1905|publisher=Henry Frowde|page=690}}</ref> Spriggans were depicted as grotesquely ugly, wizened old men with large child-like heads. They were said to be found at old ruins, [[cairn]]s, and [[Tumulus|barrow]]s guarding buried treasure.<ref name=PSK>{{cite book|title=Piskies, Spriggans, Knockers, and the Small People \u2013 Traditional Tales from Cornwall|date=c. 1979|publisher=Tor Mark Press|location=Truro|page=2|isbn=978-0850250435}}</ref> Although small, they were usually considered to be the ghosts of giants,<ref name=EDD /> with the ability to swell to enormous size. They were also said to act as [[fairy]] bodyguards.{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\nSpriggans were notorious for their unpleasant dispositions, and delighted in working mischief against those who offended them. They raised sudden whirlwinds to terrify travellers, sent storms to blight crops, and sometimes stole away mortal children, leaving their ugly [[Changeling|changelings]] in their place.<ref name=PSK /> They were blamed if a house was robbed or a building collapsed, or if cattle were stolen.<ref name=EDD /> In one story, an old woman got the better of a band of spriggans by turning her clothing inside-out (turning clothing supposedly being as effective as holy water or iron in repelling fairies) to gain their loot.<ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition, 1916, The Old Woman Who Turned Her Shift, page 113-114</ref>\nIt was not spriggans but the buccas or knockers who were associated with tin mining, acting as guardians to the workings, and apart from the mischievous nature above, their attitude to miners seems to have been one of protection.<ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition, 1916, page 82 </ref> However it is said that \"On Christmas-eve, in former days, the small people, or the spriggans, would meet at the bottom of the deepest mines, and have a midnight mass.\"<ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition 1916, page 349</ref>\n\n==Sculpture==\nA sculpture of a spriggan by [[Marilyn Collins]] can be seen in [[Crouch End]], [[London]], in some arches lining a section of the [[Parkland Walk]] (a disused railway line). If walking along the Parkland Walk from [[Finsbury Park]] to [[Highgate tube station|Highgate station]] the ''Spriggan'' is to the right just before the disused railway platforms of the former [[Crouch End railway station|Crouch End station]]. To the left, on the southside of the Parkland Walk is [[Crouch Hill Park]] where [[Ashmount School]] has been located since January 2013. The sculpture is sometimes mistaken for the [[Green Man]] or [[Pan (mythology)|Pan]].\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[Katharine Mary Briggs|Briggs, Katharine]]. ''A Dictionary of Fairies''. Penguin, 1976, {{ISBN|978-0140176582}}\n* [http://www.underground-history.co.uk/northernh3.php Underground History: The Northern Heights], Hywel Williams. Accessed 8 July 2007.\n\n{{Culture of Cornwall}}\n{{Fairies}}\n\n[[Category:Cornish culture]]\n[[Category:Cornish legendary creatures]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox mythical creature\n|name  = Spriggan\n|image     = Spriggan sculpture by Marilyn Collins, Parkland Walk, Haringey.jpg\n|caption  = Sculpture by [[Marilyn Collins]]\n|Grouping       = [[Mythological creature]] <br/> [[Fairy]] <br/> [[Sprite (creature)|Sprite]]\n|Possibilities   = \n|AKA            = \n|Country        = [[England]]\n|Region         = [[Cornwall]]\n|Habitat        = \n|First_Reported = In folklore\n|Last_Sighted   = \n|Status         = Unconfirmed\n}}\nA '''spriggan''' {{IPAc-en|s|p|r|\u026a|d\u0292|\u0259|n}} is a [[legendary creature]] from [[Cornwall|Cornish]] [[Fairy|faery]] lore. Spriggans are particularly associated with [[West Penwith]] in [[Cornwall]] <ref>Various folklore collections e.g. Craig Weatherhill and Paul Devereux, ''Myths and Legends of Cornwall'', 1994, p.23, Sigma Leisure, {{ISBN|978-1850583172}}</ref>\n\n''Spriggan'' is a dialect word, pronounced with the grapheme <gg> as /\u02a4/, sprid-jan, and not sprigg-an, borrowed from the Cornish plural ''spyrysyon'' 'spirits' <ref>Dr Ken George, ''An Gerlyver Meur'', p. 600, Cornish Language Board, {{ISBN|978-1902917849}}</ref> \n\n==In folklore==\n\"The Spriggans are found only about the cairns, coits, or cromlechs, burrows, or detached stones, with which it is unlucky for mortals to meddle. A correspondent writes: \"This is known, that they were a remarkably mischievous and thievish tribe. If ever a house was robbed, a child kidnapped, cattle carried away, or a building demolished, it was the work of the Spriggans. Whatever commotion took place in earth, air, or water, it was all put down as the work of these spirits. Wherever the giants have been, there the Spriggans have been also. It is usually considered that they are the ghosts of the giants; certainly, from many of their feats, we must suppose them to possess a giant's strength. The Spriggans have the charge of buried treasure.\"\" <ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition, 1916, p. 81, {{ISBN|978-1605064604}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[The English Dialect Dictionary]] (1905), spriggans were apparently related to the [[troll]]s of Scandinavia.<ref name=EDD>{{cite book|editor=Wright, Joseph|title=The English Dialect Dictionary|url=https://archive.org/stream/englishdialectdi05wrig#page/690/mode/1up|volume=V|year=1905|publisher=Henry Frowde|page=690}}</ref> Spriggans were depicted as grotesquely ugly, wizened old men with large child-like heads. They were said to be found at old ruins, [[cairn]]s, and [[Tumulus|barrow]]s guarding buried treasure.<ref name=PSK>{{cite book|title=Piskies, Spriggans, Knockers, and the Small People \u2013 Traditional Tales from Cornwall|date=c. 1979|publisher=Tor Mark Press|location=Truro|page=2|isbn=978-0850250435}}</ref> Although small, they were usually considered to be the ghosts of giants,<ref name=EDD /> with the ability to swell to enormous size. They were also said to act as [[fairy]] bodyguards.{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\nSpriggans were notorious for their unpleasant dispositions, and delighted in working mischief against those who offended them. They raised sudden whirlwinds to terrify travellers, sent storms to blight crops, and sometimes stole away mortal children, leaving their ugly [[Changeling|changelings]] in their place.<ref name=PSK /> They were blamed if a house was robbed or a building collapsed, or if cattle were stolen.<ref name=EDD /> In one story, an old woman got the better of a band of spriggans by turning her clothing inside-out (turning clothing supposedly being as effective as holy water or iron in repelling fairies) to gain their loot.<ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition, 1916, The Old Woman Who Turned Her Shift, page 113-114</ref>\nIt was not spriggans but the buccas or knockers who were associated with tin mining, acting as guardians to the workings, and apart from the mischievous nature above, their attitude to miners seems to have been one of protection.<ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition, 1916, page 82 </ref> However it is said that \"On Christmas-eve, in former days, the small people, or the spriggans, would meet at the bottom of the deepest mines, and have a midnight mass.\" <ref>Robert Hunt, ''Popular Romances of the West of England'', 3rd edition 1916, page 349</ref>\n\n==Sculpture==\nA sculpture of a spriggan by [[Marilyn Collins]] can be seen in [[Crouch End]], [[London]], in some arches lining a section of the [[Parkland Walk]] (a disused railway line). If walking along the Parkland Walk from [[Finsbury Park]] to [[Highgate tube station|Highgate station]] the ''Spriggan'' is to the right just before the disused railway platforms of the former [[Crouch End railway station|Crouch End station]]. To the left, on the southside of the Parkland Walk is [[Crouch Hill Park]] where [[Ashmount School]] has been located since January 2013. The sculpture is sometimes mistaken for the [[Green Man]] or [[Pan (mythology)|Pan]].\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[Katharine Mary Briggs|Briggs, Katharine]]. ''A Dictionary of Fairies''. Penguin, 1976, {{ISBN|978-0140176582}}\n* [http://www.underground-history.co.uk/northernh3.php Underground History: The Northern Heights], Hywel Williams. Accessed 8 July 2007.\n\n{{Culture of Cornwall}}\n{{Fairies}}\n\n[[Category:Cornish culture]]\n[[Category:Cornish legendary creatures]]\n", "name_user": "Giammarco Ferrari", "label": "safe", "comment": "Dots", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spriggan"}
